CAPE TOWN, March 23 – South Africa’s confirmed Covid-19 cases rose to 402 on Monday, up by 128 cases since Sunday, Health Minister Zweli Mkhize said. In the latest statistics released, Mkhize said one patient made a full recovery and was cleared to return home after testing negative for Covid-19. The Northern Cape also saw it’s first two infections, according to the statement. The breakdown of the total infections in South Africa: – Eastern Cape — two. – Free State — 13. – Gauteng — 207. – KwaZulu-Natal — 60. – Limpopo — four. – Mpumalanga — nine. – Western Cape — 100. – North West — four. – Northern Cape — two. – Unknown — one. “Current projections estimate that the virus could effect 60 percent of South Africa’s citizens at some point, but not at the same time. Most South Africans will only experience mild symptoms and humans are capable of developing immunity to the virus,” the department said. President Cyril Ramaphosa is expected to address the nation on Monday night on decisions and measures taken by the National Command Council after extensive meetings. The department added that all the South African citizens who were repatriated from Wuhan were tested and their results came back negative for Covid-19. “They will continue to be kept in quarantine for the prescribed period and will thereafter be reunified with the community.” – African News Agency (ANA)